<blockquote><p>
[O]ur self-feeling in this world depends entirely on what we <em>back</em> ourselves to be and do. It is determined by the ratio of our actualities to our supposed potentialities; a fraction of which our pretensions are the denominator and the numerator our success: thus,</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/2025-11-10-two-solutions.png" alt="https://books.google.com/books?id=JLcAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA310" width="310" height="68" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-72104" srcset="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/2025-11-10-two-solutions.png 310w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/2025-11-10-two-solutions-300x66.png 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" /></p>
<p>Such a fraction may be increased as well by diminishing the denominator as by increasing the numerator. To give up pretensions is as blessed a relief as to get them gratified; and where disappointment is incessant and the struggle unending, this is what men will always do.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&#8212; William James, <a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=JLcAAAAAMAAJ&#038;pg=PA310"><em>The Principles of Psychology</em></a>, 1890</p>
